##Is 14 days of isolation more or less? Think about it statistically

Function introduction, the interface news is China has the influence original financial and economic new media, only serves the independent thinking crowd

By Liang Jianzhang and Huang Wenzheng

Based on the known data, the probability of the incubation period of any one case exceeding 14 days is 0.838% , and the probability of exceeding 24 days is 0.062% .

Based on the known data, the probability of the incubation period of any one case exceeding 14 days is 0.838% , and the probability of exceeding 24 days is 0.062% .

”

At present, China is devoting all its efforts to control the epidemic. The good news is that the epidemic is beginning to stabilize in many areas. But at the same time, society as a whole is paying a high economic price for it. How to find a balance between control and recovery will be a difficult problem for some time now and in the future. As for the key to solve the problem, it is necessary to accurately calculate the comprehensive cost of different measures and the probability of various situations.

Basically, infectious disease is a random event, so we need to use more statistical concepts to help people deal with random events rationally, so as to avoid panic, to make good judgment and decisions. Here are two examples.

First look at concerns about the incubation period. Zhong Nanshan's team recently published a review of 1,099 cases of new coronavirus infection. This paper provides important decision support for future epidemic prevention and control work, but the conclusion that the incubation period can be as long as 24 days has caused many people to panic? Why is it 24 days now? Is the previous conclusion wrong, or has the virus mutated into something more frightening? Does the current 14-day quarantine period in place need to be extended to 24 days?

There is no need to be so alarmed. Almost all conclusions about the physiology and other characteristics of a population are subject to a degree of uncertainty. A basic knowledge of statistics is needed to better understand the implications of these findings. In Epidemiology, the incubation period of a disease can usually be approximated by log-normal distribution, and the rationality of this approximation is often explained by the reproductive dynamics of the pathogen. Put simply, this is equivalent to assuming that the "log (latency) " follows a normal distribution. Lognormal random distribution has a long tail, although the probability of the long tail is small but not zero, if the sample size is large enough, the small probability of the long tail is still possible.

The median incubation period was 3.0 days, which means the average log was 1.1 days, Zhong Nanshan's team said in their paper. The larger the standard deviation of log (incubation period) , the larger the probability of the tail of the incubation period. According to Zhong Nanshan's team's paper, the maximum incubation period was 24 days in 1,099 cases. Using Monte Carlo Simulation, we can calculate that when the standard deviation of log (incubation period) is 0.64, the median of the longest incubation period in 1099 cases is 24 days. In log-normal distribution, more than 90 percent of patients had an incubation period of less than seven days. (to calculate: (Log 7-Log 3) / 0.641.32, you can look up the normal distribution table and get a 10% probability of exceeding 1.32 standard deviations.)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
We can also simulate a 0.838% and a 0.062% probability of any one case having an incubation period of more than 14 days. It is clear that the fewer cases observed, the shorter is the maximum incubation period in these cases. If we look at only 83 cases, then the median of the longest incubation period is only 14 days. As noted above, when the number of observed cases reached 1099, the median length of the incubation period reached 24 days.

So there is no need to question Zhong Nanshan's previous conclusions or to worry that the virus has changed. It's the same virus, the same random distribution of incubation periods, only after the sample size increases, long-tail low-probability events are possible. Experts will of course go further with this, but the average person doesn't have to panic over the odds.

To make a simple analogy, if you look at 1,000 people, the maximum height could be 1.9 meters, if you look at 10,000 people, the maximum height could be more than 2 meters, we all know that there are human beings who are more than 2.2 meters tall, however, building standards in practice require only a door height of 2.0 meters. By the same token, don't worry that the current testing and quarantine regime will be upended by one or two extreme cases.

Let's take another look at the aerosol concern. There has also recently been a number of panic caused by the keyword, called "Aerosol. ". This is because it has been publicly stated that there is aerosol transmission in addition to the previously well-known direct and contact routes of transmission of new crown pneumonia. For a while people became nervous, thinking that as long as an infected person had passed through an area and breathed in the resulting "Aerosol" , it could cause others in the area to contract the virus later.

Since then, other leading experts have said that there is no evidence of COVID-19 transmission through aerosols. But even after the clarification, some members of the public still have lingering doubts about the concept. In our view, the same is true of excessive panic. As for the key to dispelling the panic, the answer remains to be sought from a statistical point of view, in the spirit of science.

The spread of the virus is also a random event, do not rule out a very small probability in a particular way to spread, but the key is how low the probability? If only a few of the tens of thousands of cases that have been diagnosed have been transmitted in a particular way, then the more accurate expression would be that, with the reliability of the four nines, the virus is only transmitted at close range. As for the "Aerosol Spread" , if there is only a theoretical possibility, but in practice it is difficult to meet the conditions of the scene, then for the vast majority of people, it is still only a very small probability threat.

In addition, we have to take into account measurement errors when we look at various types of data. In the current detection, there must be a certain number of false negative and false positive error. Suppose, for example, that there is a false positive misdiagnosis rate (that is, a false positive is misdiagnosed without the disease) , and that a certain percentage of the population has the symptoms of a common cold. When we test one hundred thousand or millions of people, there are certainly a number of people who have been diagnosed, but really it's just the regular flu. And these misdiagnosis of people have no Wuhan or close contact with the history of Wuhan. It would take the imagination of a detective novel to overstate the true infectivity of the virus if one were to try to find the source of infection for those who had been misdiagnosed. Another round of unnecessary panic.

So the most effective way to counter panic is to learn to view the news from a probabilistic and statistical point of view. The public must not lose faith in the overall statistics because of the focus on a few unfortunate events. More importantly, policymakers also need to analyse the data that is currently being presented in a calm and objective manner so as to strike a balance in policy-making and avoid extreme practices in the context of excessive panic, the pursuit of so-called "zero risk" , and the total sacrifice of other areas, resulting in the whole society to pay too high a cost.

If the economy suffers a severe blow, the resulting side effect will eventually lead to a decline in life expectancy, at the cost of another form of life. In other cases, extreme decision-making resulting from excessive panic can lead directly to an increase in other types of risk. There have been news reports, for example, of a mother in Huangmei County, Hubei Province, who had to take her daughter to a second-stage treatment for leukemia but was unable to travel to Wuhan because of road closures, nearly causing a tragedy.

We also need to be more precise about quarantine. At present, for many returning personnel, some areas are required to isolate themselves for 14 days. On the face of it, this is, of course, an attempt to minimise risk. But in fact, the return trip from the epidemic in serious areas or other areas? Have you been quarantined locally before returning? These variables can lead to vastly different levels of transmission risk, and today's blanket 14-day quarantine is clearly not the most scientific approach, and could dilute increasingly strained prevention and treatment resources at the grass-roots level.

In many places, transportation facilities and neighborhoods have taken a brutal approach based on household registration, leaving many people repeatedly isolated or even homeless. A more rational and effective approach would be to reach out to the state, organize experts, introduce rules for assessing risk and different measures for different levels of risk, and avoid duplication and excessive restrictions and segregation policies at the local level. Governments can also use mobile communications technology to estimate the risk of infection for individuals based on their short-term travel patterns, which can then be used as a basis for local restrictions. If the country's segregation and restriction rules are in place to ensure that those now entering low risk areas are at low risk, then large areas of these areas will not be required and masks will be sufficient.

In addition, the isolation time should not be zero risk, for asymptomatic people do not even need to be isolated for 14 days, as long as down to the local general population can be released. According to the mathematical model of our simple simulation estimate, 7 days of isolation can successfully screen out more than 90% of infected people, that is to reduce the risk to only the original 10% . If, for many people, isolation for seven days might be sufficient, then the economic and social costs would be significantly reduced. (mind you, our model is based on very limited data from the Zhong Nanshan article, and experts on the ground should be able to give a more accurate model.)

In the coming period of time, the epidemic prevention and control is about to enter the most critical battle. At this point, the description of any kind of random events should be considered from the point of view of probability and statistics, to understand that random events can not achieve absolute zero risk, and avoid paying extra for unrealistic pursuit. I believe everyone hopes, that society as a whole will ultimately get the best results at the lowest possible cost. To achieve this goal, we need to synthesize all kinds of data for accurate statistics and probability calculation, to help us formulate a scientific and rational policy to control the epidemic.
